    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "bc00efdf-2561-4441-af1a-3941b9c4aac4",
      "text": "Novoselov is known for his interest in art. He practices in Chinese traditional drawing and has been involved in several projects on modern art - [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Konstantin_Novoselov#Art_involvement wikipedia]"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "8b08e2f0-3213-4bed-9257-81641cc57209",
      "text": "Thus, in February 2015 he combined forces with [[Cornelia Parker]] to create a display for the opening of the [[Whitworth Art Gallery]]. Cornelia Parker's meteorite shower firework (pieces of meteorites loaded in firework) was launched by Novoselov breathing on graphene gas sensor (which changed the resistance of graphene due to doping by water vapour). \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "bff1baccafb99cdd",
      "text": "[[Graphene]] was obtained through exfoliation of [[graphite]] which was extracted from a drawing of [[William Blake]]. Novoselov suggested that he also exfoliated graphite obtained from the drawings of other prominent artists: [[John Constable]], [[Pablo Picasso]], [[J. M. W. Turner]], [[Thomas Girtin]]. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ddafe8ea2a188751",
      "text": "He said that only microscopic amounts (flake size less than 100 micrometres) was extracted from each of the drawings. In 2015 he participated in \"in conversation\" session with [[Douglas Gordon]] during Interdependence session at [[Manchester International Festival]]."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "00bd46d3-ea95-4915-aeb6-52a97e62189c",
      "text": "# Art and science\n\nHe also participates in discussions on the relation between art and science. Novoselov believes that artists and scientists both rely on curiosity, willingness to learn and imagination:"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "033d0151-e0e2-4937-8a88-bd75070b794e",
      "text": "Novoselov is fond of Chinese calligraphy and drawing. He learned it from a prominent Chinese artist [[Zheng Shenglong]]. Nine ink paintings by Prof. Novoselov were shown at the exhibition \"Britain Through the Eyes of a Chinese Diplomat\" at the University of Leeds."
